Not sure if we can tidy up but those 4 steps to edit a Leave Request and go to Manage Time has been duplicated in many classes around the selenium code base.

We could have a method which receive a DisplayCasePage, execute those steps and return a SelectedLeavePlanManageTimePage, like:

DisplayCasePage.goToManageTime();

That&#39;s not duplicated but if you didn&#39;t understand the purpose of those 2 methods I failed on naming it properly and providing a good java doc, I&#39;ve seen huge methods (include some of mine) with duplicated code for joins. Actually we can reuse those two methods for many tables you want, you can look at DecisionDayService.getAllowedDaysForActualReportedTimeBySelectedLeavePlan() and you&#39;ll a union all query with a total of 10 joins just using those two methods.

If you look deeper you&#39;ll see those methods are slightly different, that&#39;s because we could have joins which goes &#39;forward and back&#39; in the tables, example for a DecisionDay Query:

For this simple join: DecisionDay &gt; SelectedLeavePlan &gt; LeaveRequest

we&#39;ll use only addSecondTableJoin, like (simplified way):

addSecondTableJoin(query, DecisionDay, SelectedLeavePlan);
addSecondTableJoin(query, SelectedLeavePlan, LeaveRequest);

I named it as &#39;second table join&#39; because you&#39;re providing to the method two tables (first and second where the first has the foreign key to the second) and method will consider that first table is already referenced in query and it will only the second table as join on the query. But some times we have more complex scenarios where the join can go forward and back like:

DecisionDay &gt; SelectedLeavePlan &gt; LeaveRequest -
                                               |
AbsencePeriodDecision &lt; TimeOffAbsencePeriod &lt; -

For that more complex join above, the usage would be:

addSecondTableJoin(query, DecisionDay, SelectedLeavePlan);
addSecondTableJoin(query, SelectedLeavePlan, LeaveRequest);
// LeaveRequest was already added to the query
addFirstTableJoin(query, TimeOffAbsencePeriod, LeaveRequest);
addFirstTableJoin(query, AbsencePeriodDecision, TimeOffAbsencePeriod);

That&#39;s why we need 2 methods, makes sense? If you have any suggestion let me know, for now I&#39;ll provide more details on the javadoc.

